 of peoples past; the second posits a generational taking of turns that Matthias Fritsch applies to both our institutions and our natural environment, in other words, to the earth as a whole. Offering new readings of key philosophers, and emphasizing the work of Emmanuel Levinas and Jacques Derrida in particular, Taking Turns with the Earth disrupts human-centered notions of terrestrial appropriation and sharing to give us a new continental philosophical account of future-oriented justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDeconstruction. 0aEnvironmental ethics. 0aFuture, ThexPhilosophy. 0aFuture, The. 0aPhenomenology. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny20th century. 0aPhilosophy, Modern. 0aSocial justicexPhilosophy. 0aSocial justice. 4aDerrida. 4aLevinas. 4adeconstruction. 4afuture generations. 4aintergenerational justice. 4aphenomenology. 4areciprocity. 4ataking turns. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360696840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606968423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606968.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles